]][[ja:%E9%9C%9C%E6%9C%88%E7%A5%9E%E6%A5%BD]]]][[ja:'''Shimotsuki Kagura''' (霜月神楽) refers to {{ill|Kagura|ja|神楽}} performances held during the 11th month of the old lunar calendar (霜月), corresponding to {{ill|December|ja|12月}} through {{ill|January|ja|1月}} of the following year in the Gregorian calendar. It is also known as '''{{ill|Yudate Kagura|ja|湯立神楽}}''' because it is often performed in conjunction with the {{ill|Yudate|ja|湯立}} ritual. Additionally, as it is believed to be modeled after the kagura of the {{ill|Outer Shrine of Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮外宮}}, it is sometimes called '''{{ill|Ise-ryū Kagura|ja|伊勢流神楽}}'''.== Overview ==Kagura was traditionally considered an event to be held in the 11th month of the old calendar. In {{ill|ancient|ja|古代}} and {{ill|medieval Japan|ja|中世}}, the kagura of the {{ill|Sonkara Shrine|ja|園韓神社}} at the Imperial Court was performed in November. Additionally, on the 13th day of the 11th lunar month, kagura ceremonies (known as {{ill|Yoriai Kagura|ja|寄合神楽}} and {{ill|Hōnō Kagura|ja|奉納神楽}}) were held at the residence of the {{ill|Hitokuchi Tōdai-fu|ja|一口頭大夫}} by the {{ill|Goshi of Ise Grand Shrine|ja|御師}}.Although the kagura of the Ise Goshi declined during the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代}}, it had previously spread across Japan, blending with elements of {{ill|Kumano faith|ja|熊野信仰}}, {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道}}, {{ill|Onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道}}, and {{ill|Shushō-e|ja|修正会}}.In the old calendar, November was considered a time when the gods and nature weakened. Therefore, kagura was performed to revitalize and renew the spirit in preparation for the new year. Rituals from Kumano, such as purification with sacred hot water (湯の清まり) and secluded purification practices (忌籠), were incorporated, becoming the basis for Yudate.The ritual stage (庭, niwa) is adorned with sacred symbols such as {{ill|Gohei|ja|御幣}} and {{ill|Himorogi|ja|神籬}}. A hot water cauldron (湯釜, yugama) is placed at the center, with canopies representing clouds and the heavens hanging above. Sacred ropes ({{ill|Shimenawa|ja|注連縄}}) and paper decorations ({{ill|Kirigami|ja|切紙飾}}) encircle the area to welcome the gods. Throughout the night, various prayers, ritual recitations, and kagura dances performed by priests and participants are conducted around the cauldron.While the specific methods of Shimotsuki Kagura vary by region and shrine, the general ritual sequence includes drawing sacred water from rivers or waterfalls, heating it in cauldrons, offering it to the gods, and sprinkling it on participants for purification ({{ill|Harae|ja|祓}} and {{ill|Misogi|ja|禊}}). The ceremony begins with the reading of a {{ill|Shinmeichō|ja|神名帳}} (register of invited deities), followed by:- Inviting the gods with maskless dances (採物舞, torimono-mai)- Offering praises (願上, negaiage)- Sending off the deities around midnight (神送り, kami-okuri)- A sacred feast (直会, naorai)- Later-night performances featuring masked characters like demons and elders (面形舞, omote-mai)- A final blessing ceremonySpecial honors are given to local deities, even if they are of lower rank, due to their deep connection with the community.== Notable Shimotsuki Kagura Performances ==]][[File:Toyama's Shimotsuki Festival 001.JPG|thumb|Statue from the {{ill|Toyama Shimotsuki Festival|ja|遠山の霜月祭}}. A hot spring (飲泉) modeled after the Yudate ritual is visible on the right, and the water is drinkable. Photo taken at {{ill|Michi-no-Eki Toyama-go|ja|道の駅遠山郷}} in 2009 ({{ill|Heisei 21|ja|平成21年}}).]]]][[ja:Here are some representative examples of Shimotsuki Kagura. Many other kagura traditions that have preserved parts or all of the Shimotsuki Kagura ritual can be found throughout Japan.- {{ill|Horowasan no Shimotsuki Kagura|ja|保呂羽山の霜月神楽}}: A traditional folk performance designated as an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財}} in {{ill|Ōmori, Yokote City, Akita Prefecture|ja|秋田県横手市大森町八沢木}}.- {{ill|Tenryū-mura no Shimotsuki Kagura|ja|天龍村の霜月神楽}}: A designated Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property in {{ill|Tenryū Village, Shimoina District, Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県下伊那郡天龍村}}.- {{ill|Tōyama no Shimotsuki Matsuri|ja|遠山の霜月祭}}: A festival held in former {{ill|Minami-Shinano Village|ja|南信濃村}} and {{ill|Kamimura|ja|上村 (長野県)}} in {{ill|Iida City, Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県飯田市}}, designated as an Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property.- {{ill|Hana Matsuri (Shimotsuki Kagura)|ja|花祭 (霜月神楽)}}: A traditional folk performance designated as an Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property in the {{ill|Okumikawa|ja|奥三河}} region of {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県}}.== References ==* Itaya Toru, "Shimotsuki Kagura," in *{{ill|Nihon Rekishi Daijiten|ja|日本歴史大事典}}* 2 ({{ill|Shogakukan|ja|小学館}}, 2000), ISBN 978-4-095-23002-3.* Kubota Hiromichi, "Shimotsuki Kagura," in *Nihon Minzoku Daijiten* Vol. 1 ({{ill|Yoshikawa Kōbunkan|ja|吉川弘文館}}, 1998), ISBN 978-4-642-01332-1.* Yamaji Kōzō, "Shimotsuki Kagura," in *Nihonshi Daijiten* 3 ({{ill|Heibonsha|ja|平凡社}}, 1993), ISBN 978-4-582-13103-1.* Aoki Shūhei, "Shimotsuki Kagura," in *{{ill|Kokushi Daijiten|ja|国史大辞典}}* 7 (Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 1986), ISBN 978-4-642-00507-4.== See Also ==* {{ill|Winter Festivals|ja|冬祭り}}]][[Category:Kagura]]]][[Category:redirect]]
